      <div style="font-size: 12px; color: #555; margin-bottom: 40px;">8 min read · Display Technology</div>
      
      <div class="article-content" style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.8; color: #ccc;">

        <p>Motion blur is one of the most common complaints about LCD and OLED monitors, yet it is widely misunderstood. There are actually two distinct types of motion blur that affect your display: <strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">persistence blur</strong> caused by sample-and-hold technology, and <strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">response-time blur</strong> caused by slow pixel transitions. Both reduce image clarity during motion, but they have completely different causes and different solutions.</p>

        <h2>What is Sample-and-Hold Motion Blur?</h2>
        <p>Modern flat-panel displays — whether LCD or OLED — use a technology called sample-and-hold. When a new frame is rendered, the display draws it and then holds that static image perfectly still on the screen until the next frame arrives. Your monitor does not flash and go dark between frames the way a CRT electron gun would; it simply locks the frame in place.</p>
        <p>The problem arises because your eyes are not static. When a moving object appears on screen, your eyes instinctively track it with a smooth pursuit motion. While your eyes move, the display holds its frame completely still. The result is that the moving object smears across your retina — not because the monitor is slow, but because your biology is working against the technology.</p>

        <div style="background:#111; border:1px solid #2a2a2a; border-left:3px solid #39ff14; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:6px; margin:24px 0;">
          <strong style="color:#39ff14; font-size:12px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.08em;">Key Insight</strong>
          <p style="margin:8px 0 0; font-size:13px; color:#ccc;">Persistence blur is a fundamental property of sample-and-hold displays. It exists even when a display has a <em>perfect</em> 0ms pixel response time. The only way to eliminate it is to reduce the duration each frame is visible — which means higher refresh rates or BFI strobing.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The Refresh Rate Solution to Persistence Blur</h2>
        <p>Because persistence blur is driven by how long a frame stays on screen, the most effective solution is to increase your refresh rate. At 60Hz, each frame is displayed for ~16.7ms. At 144Hz, each frame lasts only ~6.9ms. At 360Hz, a frame stays on screen for just ~2.8ms. The shorter the hold period, the less time your eye has to drift, and the less blur you perceive.</p>

        <p>This relationship is described by Blur Busters Law: perceived motion blur in pixels is approximately equal to your eye-tracking speed (in pixels per frame) multiplied by the frame hold duration. The formula demonstrates that doubling your refresh rate roughly halves your motion blur — one of the most powerful reasons to upgrade from 60Hz to 144Hz.</p>

        <div style="overflow-x:auto; margin:24px 0;">
          <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:13px;">
